{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17526049","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17526049"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:20:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:20:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14116"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14116","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14116"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.17,0.06,0.27,0.48]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6796"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83086"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6796","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6796"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14116"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68148"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"42"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"2321"},{"type":"tags","id":"2469"},{"type":"tags","id":"4340"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"10779"},{"type":"tags","id":"11631"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12119"},{"type":"tags","id":"12121"},{"type":"tags","id":"12799"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15179"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19451"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43490"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83086","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/83086"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 23-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic to discuss ceasing contraception in order to start attempting to conceive with her partner. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe asks about a genetic test she read about online for people planning to become pregnant to assess if they are at risk of having a baby with a significant medical problem. In response to her question, you discuss reproductive genetic carrier screening with the patient.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following sets of genetic conditions is included as part of the standard reproductive genetic carrier screening?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Spinal Muscular Atrophy (SMA), Congenital adrenal hyperplasia (CAH) and Angelman Syndrome (AS)","Duchenne Muscular Dystrophy (DMD), Cystic Fibrosis (CFTR) and Phenylketonuria (PKU)","Huntington\u0027s Disease (HD), Sickle cell anemia (SCD) and Congenital adrenal hyperplasia (CAH)","Trisomy 21 (T21), Trisomy 18 (T18) and Trisomy 13 (T13)","Fragile X Syndrome (FXS), Spinal Muscular Atrophy (SMA) and Cystic Fibrosis (CFTR)"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe standard reproductive genetic carrier screening typically includes testing for three conditions: \u003Cstrong\u003EFragile X Syndrome (FXS), Spinal Muscular Atrophy (SMA), and Cystic Fibrosis (CFTR)\u003C/strong\u003E. These conditions are chosen because they are relatively common, have a significant impact on quality of life, and can be detected through carrier screening.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpinal Muscular Atrophy (SMA)\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003ECongenital adrenal hyperplasia (CAH)\u003C/strong\u003E are indeed genetic conditions that can be screened for, but Angelman Syndrome is not typically part of the standard screening panel.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDuchenne Muscular Dystrophy (DMD)\u003C/strong\u003E is an X-linked disorder primarily affecting males, \u003Cstrong\u003ECystic Fibrosis (CFTR)\u003C/strong\u003E is included in the standard panel, and \u003Cstrong\u003EPhenylketonuria (PKU)\u003C/strong\u003E is typically screened for in newborns rather than in carrier screening.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHuntington\u0027s Disease (HD)\u003C/strong\u003E is an autosomal dominant disorder and not typically included in carrier screening. \u003Cstrong\u003ESickle cell anemia (SCD)\u003C/strong\u003E screening may be offered based on ethnic background, and \u003Cstrong\u003ECongenital adrenal hyperplasia (CAH)\u003C/strong\u003E is not part of the standard panel.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrisomy 21 (T21), Trisomy 18 (T18), and Trisomy 13 (T13)\u003C/strong\u003E are chromosomal abnormalities that are typically screened for during pregnancy through non-invasive prenatal testing (NIPT) or other prenatal screening methods, not through pre-conception carrier screening.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EReproductive genetic carrier screening is recommended for all women who are planning pregnancy or in early pregnancy. It\u0027s important to note that being a carrier usually doesn\u0027t affect the individual\u0027s health, but if both partners are carriers for the same condition, there\u0027s a risk of having a child with that condition. This screening allows couples to make informed decisions about their reproductive options, including prenatal diagnosis, preimplantation genetic testing, use of donor gametes, or adoption.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Reproductive genetic carrier screening typically includes testing for Fragile X Syndrome (FXS), Spinal Muscular Atrophy (SMA), and Cystic Fibrosis (CFTR).","Reproductive genetic carrier screening is recommended for all women planning pregnancy or in early pregnancy.","Carrier screening can identify couples at risk of having a child with a severe genetic condition, allowing for informed reproductive decision-making."],"references":["Reproductive Carrier Screening. In: RANZCOG [online]. 2019 Feb;51:S36. Available at: https://ranzcog.edu.au/RANZCOG_SITE/media/RANZCOG-MEDIA/Women%27s%20Health/Patient%20information/Carrier-Screening-1st-Edition.pdf?ext=.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68148"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14116"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68148","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/68148"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-01T23:21:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-01T23:21:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6796"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83086"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"42","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/42"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddec","name":"Genetics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":